## 2. Differences Between Virtual and Conventional Classrooms

### 2.1 Communication and Interaction

```latex
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Conventional Classroom:}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Face-to-face interaction is the primary mode.
        \item Non-verbal cues (e.g., body language, eye contact) are easily perceived.
        \item Real-time discussions and collaborative activities are common.
    \end{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Virtual Classroom:}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Communication is mainly through text, audio, or video.
        \item Non-verbal cues are limited or absent.
        \item Asynchronous communication is common (e.g., discussion forums, emails).
    \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
```

### 2.2 Classroom Management

```latex
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Conventional Classroom:}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Teachers can manage behavior and participation in real time.
        \item Students are physically present, making supervision easier.
        \item In-person discipline can be more immediate and effective.
    \end{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Virtual Classroom:}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Management is more challenging due to distractions (e.g., background noise, multitasking).
        \item Teachers must rely on software tools (e.g., monitoring systems, polls) to manage participation.
        \item Ensuring student engagement requires proactive strategies.
    \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
```

